1
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:21,800
Was it all just a dream?

2
00:00:21,960 --> 00:00:25,160
God bless you, Florida! Thank you!

3
00:00:25,320 --> 00:00:29,040
Did the last four years
not really happen?

4
00:00:29,240 --> 00:00:33,240
Look, there's Ben Affleck.
He's often in my dreams.

5
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:36,280
And the Taxi Driver guy.
He was there too.

6
00:00:36,360 --> 00:00:39,040
And little Stevie Wonder,
he seemed so happy...

7
00:00:39,240 --> 00:00:42,560
...like a miracle had taken place.

8
00:00:43,400 --> 00:00:45,600
Was it a dream?

9
00:00:45,800 --> 00:00:47,120
We want Gore!

10
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:49,120
Or was it real?

11
00:00:51,160 --> 00:00:54,680
It was election night 2000, and things
seemed to be going as planned.

12
00:00:54,840 --> 00:00:57,440
In New York, Al Gore is
our projected winner.

13
00:00:57,640 --> 00:00:59,240
The Garden State is green for Gore.

14
00:00:59,280 --> 00:01:04,280
We project Mr. Gore the winner in
Delaware. This state has voted with...

15
00:01:04,480 --> 00:01:06,680
Excuse me, one second.
I'm sorry to interrupt.

16
00:01:06,760 --> 00:01:09,040
Mike, I wouldn't do this
if it weren't big.

17
00:01:09,240 --> 00:01:11,360
Florida goes for Al Gore.

18
00:01:11,520 --> 00:01:15,800
CNN announces that we call Florida
in the Al Gore column.

19
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:19,960
Then something called the Fox News
Channel called the election...

20
00:01:20,160 --> 00:01:21,480
...in favor of the other guy.

21
00:01:21,680 --> 00:01:25,480
Fox News now projects George
W. Bush the winner in Florida...

22
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:29,040
...and thus it appears the winner of the
presidency of the United States.

23
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:31,200
All of a sudden, the other
networks said:

24
00:01:31,400 --> 00:01:34,200
"Hey, if Fox said it, it must be true. "

25
00:01:34,360 --> 00:01:37,160
All of us at the networks made
a mistake...

26
00:01:37,240 --> 00:01:40,560
...and projected Florida
in the Al Gore column.

27
00:01:40,600 --> 00:01:42,120
It was our mistake.

28
00:01:42,320 --> 00:01:45,120
What most people don't know is
that the man in charge...

29
00:01:45,160 --> 00:01:47,560
...of the decision desk at Fox
that night...

30
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:49,480
...the man who called it for Bush...

31
00:01:49,560 --> 00:01:53,080
...was none other than Bush's
first cousin John Ellis.

32
00:01:53,240 --> 00:01:56,320
How does someone like Bush get
away with something like this?

33
00:01:59,680 --> 00:02:03,400
Well, first, it helps if your brother is
the governor of the state in question.

34
00:02:03,560 --> 00:02:07,360
You know something? We are gonna
win Florida. Mark my words.

35
00:02:07,560 --> 00:02:09,040
You can write it down.

36
00:02:09,200 --> 00:02:11,320
Second, make sure
your campaign chairman...

37
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:15,320
...is also the vote-count woman
and that her state hires a company...

38
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:20,680
...to knock voters off the rolls
who aren't likely to vote for you.

39
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:24,040
You can usually tell them
by the color of their skin.

40
00:02:24,120 --> 00:02:27,320
Then make sure your side fights
like it's life or death.

41
00:02:27,480 --> 00:02:28,880
This talk about legitimacy
is overblown.

42
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:33,640
President Bush! President Bush!

43
00:02:37,600 --> 00:02:39,000
And hope the other side
sits by.

44
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:41,600
And even if numerous independent
investigations...

45
00:02:41,800 --> 00:02:43,920
...prove that Gore got the
most votes...

46
00:02:43,960 --> 00:02:46,560
If there was a statewide recount,
Gore won the election.

47
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:51,120
...it won't matter, as long as all
your daddy's friends...

48
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:54,640
...on the Supreme Court vote
the right way.

49
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:59,800
While I strongly disagree with
the court's decision, I accept it.

50
00:02:59,960 --> 00:03:02,360
What we need now is acceptance.

51
00:03:04,040 --> 00:03:06,440
We have a new president-elect.

52
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:13,600
It turns out none of this was a dream.
It's what really happened.

53
00:03:15,160 --> 00:03:18,280
On the day the joint session of both
the House of Representatives...

54
00:03:18,440 --> 00:03:22,040
...and the Senate was to certify
the election results...

55
00:03:22,240 --> 00:03:24,920
...Al Gore, in his dual role
as outgoing vice president...

56
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:26,680
...and president of the Senate...

57
00:03:28,360 --> 00:03:31,360
...presided over the event
that would officially anoint...

58
00:03:31,560 --> 00:03:34,160
...George W. Bush
as the new president.

59
00:03:34,320 --> 00:03:39,000
If any congressman wanted to raise
an objection, the rules insisted...

60
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:44,000
...that he or she had to have the
signed support of just one senator.

61
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:48,480
Mr. President, and I take great pride
in calling you that...

62
00:03:48,520 --> 00:03:51,440
...I must object because
of the overwhelming evidence...

63
00:03:51,480 --> 00:03:55,400
...of misconduct, deliberate fraud
and an attempt to suppress voter...

64
00:03:55,480 --> 00:04:00,080
The chair must remind members
that under Section 18 of Title 3...

65
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:03,240
...United States Code, no debate
is allowed in the joint session.

66
00:04:03,400 --> 00:04:05,800
Thank you, Mr. President.
To answer your question...

67
00:04:05,920 --> 00:04:09,720
...the objection is in writing, signed
by a number of members...

68
00:04:09,880 --> 00:04:14,080
...of the House of Representatives,
but not by a member of the Senate.

69
00:04:14,240 --> 00:04:18,720
Mr. President, it is in writing and
signed by several House colleagues...

70
00:04:18,920 --> 00:04:23,720
...on behalf, and myself, of the 27,000
voters of Duval County...

71
00:04:23,800 --> 00:04:27,400
...in which 16,000 of them are
African-Americans...

72
00:04:27,560 --> 00:04:31,360
...that was disenfranchised
in this last election.

73
00:04:31,520 --> 00:04:33,800
Is the objection signed by a member
of the Senate?

74
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,520
Not signed by a member
of the Senate.

75
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:38,400
The Senate is missing.

76
00:04:38,480 --> 00:04:40,760
It is in writing and signed
by myself...

77
00:04:40,960 --> 00:04:43,360
...on behalf of many
of the diverse constituents...

78
00:04:43,520 --> 00:04:46,320
...especially those
in the 9th Congressional District...

79
00:04:46,440 --> 00:04:49,520
...and all American voters who
recognize that the Supreme Court...

80
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:52,600
...not the people of the United States,
decided this election.

81
00:04:52,680 --> 00:04:55,200
Is the objection signed
by a senator?

82
00:04:55,360 --> 00:04:59,560
Unfortunately, Mr. President, it is
not signed by one single senator.

83
00:04:59,640 --> 00:05:03,440
I have no authority
over the United States Senate...

84
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:05,120
...and no senator has signed.

85
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:08,920
Mr. President, it is in writing and
signed by myself and several...

86
00:05:08,960 --> 00:05:13,960
...of my constituents from Florida.
A senator is needed, but missing.

87
00:05:14,120 --> 00:05:17,120
Is the objection in writing...

88
00:05:17,280 --> 00:05:20,680
...and signed by a member
of the House and a senator?

89
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:23,080
The objection is in writing,
and I don't care...

90
00:05:23,160 --> 00:05:27,760
...that it is not signed by a member
of the Senate.

91
00:05:27,960 --> 00:05:30,840
The chair will advise that the rules
do care...

92
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:36,320
...and the signature of a senator...

93
00:05:37,360 --> 00:05:42,280
Not a single senator came to the aid
of the African-Americans in Congress.

94
00:05:42,440 --> 00:05:47,240
One after another, they were told
to sit down and shut up.

95
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:50,400
It's a sad day in America,
Mr. President, when we can't find...

96
00:05:50,480 --> 00:05:53,480
...a senator to sign the objections...

97
00:05:53,640 --> 00:05:56,640
- The gentleman will suspend...
- New Democratic senators won't sign.

98
00:05:56,840 --> 00:06:00,640
- I object.
- The gentleman will suspend.

99
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:05,120
Inauguration coverage, 2001...

100
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:08,760
...on a nasty, but it could be worse,
kind of day in Washington.

101
00:06:08,920 --> 00:06:10,640
- What do we want?
- Justice!

102
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:12,120
- When do we want it?
- Now!

103
00:06:13,040 --> 00:06:15,920
On the day George W. Bush was
inaugurated...

104
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:20,080
...tens of thousands of Americans
poured into the streets of D. C...

105
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:23,440
...in one last attempt to reclaim
what had been taken from them.

106
00:06:27,600 --> 00:06:30,320
They pelted Bush's limo with eggs...

107
00:06:30,520 --> 00:06:32,200
Stay back! Get back!

108
00:06:32,280 --> 00:06:34,880
...and brought the inauguration
parade to a halt.

109
00:06:36,280 --> 00:06:39,480
The plan to have Bush get out
of the limo for the traditional walk...

110
00:06:39,520 --> 00:06:41,840
...to the White House
was scrapped.

111
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:46,840
Bush's limo hit the gas to prevent
an even larger riot.

112
00:06:46,880 --> 00:06:51,600
No president had ever witnessed
such a thing on his inauguration day.

113
00:06:58,120 --> 00:07:04,320
And for the next eight months, it didn't
get any better for George W. Bush.

114
00:07:04,560 --> 00:07:08,760
He couldn't get his judges appointed,
he struggled to pass his legislation...

115
00:07:10,840 --> 00:07:13,720
...and he lost Republican control
of the Senate.

116
00:07:14,680 --> 00:07:18,280
His approval ratings in the polls
began to sink.

117
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:21,840
He was already beginning to look
like a lame-duck president.

118
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:26,440
With everything going wrong,
he did what any of us would do.

119
00:07:26,600 --> 00:07:29,120
He went on vacation.

120
00:07:41,880 --> 00:07:43,080
Oh, no!

121
00:07:43,280 --> 00:07:46,680
In his first eight months in office
before September 11 th...

122
00:07:46,760 --> 00:07:50,760
...George W. Bush was on vacation,
according to The Washington Post...

123
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:52,760
...42 percent of the time.

124
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:55,920
If I hit every shot good, people would
say I wasn't working.

125
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:00,000
It was not surprising that Mr. Bush
needed some time off.

126
00:08:00,160 --> 00:08:02,680
Being president is a lot of work.

127
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:06,280
What about these folks that say that
you're taking too long of a vacation?

128
00:08:07,840 --> 00:08:11,040
They don't understand the definition
of work, then.

129
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:16,400
I'm getting a lot done. You don't
have to be in Washington to work.

130
00:08:16,560 --> 00:08:21,760
It's amazing what can happen
with telephones and faxes.

131
00:08:21,920 --> 00:08:23,920
Thank you so much.

132
00:08:24,120 --> 00:08:25,920
- Is this to Destiny and Bubba?
- Yeah.

133
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:28,560
What are you doing the rest
of the day?

134
00:08:28,760 --> 00:08:31,680
Karen Hughes is coming over.
We're working on some things.

135
00:08:31,840 --> 00:08:37,120
And she'll be over here. We're working
on a few things, a few matters.

136
00:08:37,240 --> 00:08:42,320
I'm working on some initiatives.
We're... You'll see.

137
00:08:42,480 --> 00:08:45,280
There'll be some decisions
I will have made while I'm here.

138
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:47,560
We'll be announcing them
as time goes on.

139
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:51,760
The first time I met him, he had
some good advice for me.

140
00:08:51,920 --> 00:08:53,800
Governor Bush, it's Michael Moore.

141
00:08:53,920 --> 00:08:58,320
Behave yourself, will you?
Go find real work.

142
00:08:58,360 --> 00:09:01,680
And work was something he knew
a lot about.

143
00:09:01,840 --> 00:09:03,840
- Anybody want some grits?
- Yeah.

144
00:09:04,440 --> 00:09:08,440
Relaxing at Camp David.
Yachting off Kennebunkport.

145
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,480
How you doing?

146
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:14,200
Or being a cowboy on the ranch
in Texas.

147
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:16,240
I love nature, getting
in the truck with my dogs.

148
00:09:17,920 --> 00:09:19,120
Oh, hi.

149
00:09:19,320 --> 00:09:22,120
George Bush spent the rest
of August at the ranch...

150
00:09:22,320 --> 00:09:24,400
...where life was less complicated.

151
00:09:24,560 --> 00:09:28,080
Armadillos love to dig the soil
looking for bugs.

152
00:09:28,280 --> 00:09:30,280
And...

153
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:35,040
So I went out there the other day,
and there was Barney...

154
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:39,600
...buried in this hole,
chasing an armadillo.

155
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:41,800
It was a summer to remember.

156
00:09:42,560 --> 00:09:45,040
Afterward, he left Texas for
his second-favorite place.

157
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:50,600
On September 10th, he joined
his brother in Florida...

158
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:54,920
...where they looked at files
and met important Floridians.

159
00:09:55,480 --> 00:10:01,760
He went to sleep that night in a bed
made with fine French linens.

160
00:10:18,600 --> 00:10:20,400
Do you suppose he's pretty
confident...

161
00:10:20,480 --> 00:10:22,880
...on those numbers on Iraqi
security forces?

162
00:11:51,560 --> 00:11:54,360
Make me look young.

163
00:12:05,160 --> 00:12:07,960
Yeah, I've got a little,
sort of air noise.

164
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:11,560
Yeah, just don't turn it up too much.
I don't want to blow my head off.

165
00:12:17,880 --> 00:12:19,960
I got a mike here
if they want to use it.

166
00:12:20,080 --> 00:12:23,160
Testing, one, two. This is
the Oval Office. Testing, one, two.

167
00:12:23,320 --> 00:12:26,720
Testing, one, two.
This is the Oval Office.

168
00:12:28,600 --> 00:12:31,600
Testing, one, two, three, four, five.

169
00:13:28,880 --> 00:13:31,480
We have something that has
happened here...

170
00:13:31,640 --> 00:13:34,560
...at the World Trade Center.
We noticed a flame...

171
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:37,360
...and an awful lot of smoke...

172
00:13:44,960 --> 00:13:47,160
This is horrible.

173
00:13:57,800 --> 00:14:00,280
- Oh, my God!
- Oh, my God.

174
00:14:00,360 --> 00:14:02,640
Oh, my, dear.

175
00:14:05,520 --> 00:14:08,800
Let's go! Let's go, back!
Come on, let's go!

176
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:11,520
Oh, my God!

177
00:14:13,480 --> 00:14:19,760
Save their souls, Lord.
Save their souls, Lord.

178
00:14:21,080 --> 00:14:24,880
Oh, they're jumping.

179
00:16:04,880 --> 00:16:07,560
On September 11 th, 2001,
nearly 3000 people...

180
00:16:09,480 --> 00:16:12,760
...including a colleague of mine,
Bill Weems...

181
00:16:12,920 --> 00:16:17,320
...were killed in the largest foreign
attack ever on American soil.

182
00:16:18,680 --> 00:16:21,880
The targets were the financial
and military headquarters...

183
00:16:22,040 --> 00:16:23,840
...of the United States.

184
00:16:24,040 --> 00:16:29,240
If anyone has any idea or they've seen
him or knows where he is, to call us.

185
00:16:29,400 --> 00:16:33,600
He's got two little babies.
Two little babies.

186
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:37,080
As the attack took place,
Mr. Bush was on his way...

187
00:16:37,280 --> 00:16:40,080
...to an elementary school
in Florida.

188
00:16:40,240 --> 00:16:43,920
When informed of the first plane
hitting the World Trade Center...

189
00:16:44,080 --> 00:16:47,480
...where terrorists had struck
just eight years prior...

190
00:16:47,680 --> 00:16:51,480
...Mr. Bush decided to go ahead
with his photo opportunity.

191
00:16:51,640 --> 00:16:53,760
- Good morning, boys and girls.
- Good morning.

192
00:16:53,960 --> 00:16:55,760
Good morning.

193
00:16:56,600 --> 00:16:58,520
Read this word the fast way.
Get ready.

194
00:16:58,720 --> 00:17:00,320
- "Mad"!
- Yes. Get ready.

195
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:03,920
- "Calf"!
- Yeah.

196
00:17:04,080 --> 00:17:07,280
Get ready to read the words on this
page without making a mistake.

197
00:17:07,440 --> 00:17:09,720
When the second plane hit
the tower...

198
00:17:09,840 --> 00:17:12,240
...his chief of staff entered
the classroom...

199
00:17:12,440 --> 00:17:17,520
...and told Mr. Bush,
"The nation is under attack. "

200
00:17:20,160 --> 00:17:25,160
Not knowing what to do, with no one
telling him what to do...

201
00:17:25,320 --> 00:17:29,600
...and no Secret Service rushing
in to take him to safety...

202
00:17:29,800 --> 00:17:32,000
...Mr. Bush just sat there...

203
00:17:32,160 --> 00:17:37,480
...and continued to read
My Pet Goat with the children.

204
00:17:51,040 --> 00:17:54,240
Nearly seven minutes passed
with nobody doing anything.

205
00:17:59,960 --> 00:18:02,480
As Bush sat in that Florida
classroom...

206
00:18:02,680 --> 00:18:05,160
...was he wondering if maybe
he should have shown up...

207
00:18:05,320 --> 00:18:07,120
...to work more often?

208
00:18:07,320 --> 00:18:10,640
Should he have held at least one
meeting since taking office...

209
00:18:10,680 --> 00:18:15,680
...to discuss the threat of terrorism
with his head of counterterrorism?

210
00:18:18,240 --> 00:18:22,360
Maybe Bush wondered why he had
cut terrorism funding from the FBI.

211
00:18:22,400 --> 00:18:25,720
Or perhaps he just should have read
the security briefing...

212
00:18:25,800 --> 00:18:29,120
...that was given to him on
August 6th, 2001...

213
00:18:29,280 --> 00:18:31,280
...which said Osama bin Laden
was planning...

214
00:18:32,840 --> 00:18:35,840
...to attack America by hijacking
airplanes.

215
00:18:38,040 --> 00:18:41,520
Maybe he wasn't worried, because
the title of the report was too vague.

216
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:44,200
I believe the title was
"Bin Laden Determined...

217
00:18:44,360 --> 00:18:46,240
...to Attack Inside the United States. "

218
00:18:46,960 --> 00:18:50,560
A report like that might make
some men jump...

219
00:18:50,720 --> 00:18:55,200
...but, as in days past,
George W. Just went fishing.

220
00:18:55,760 --> 00:19:01,480
As the minutes went by, George Bush
continued to sit in the classroom.

221
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:07,120
Was he thinking, "I've been hanging
out with the wrong crowd.

222
00:19:09,080 --> 00:19:12,800
Which one of them screwed me?

223
00:19:13,560 --> 00:19:16,560
Was it the guy my daddy's friends
delivered a lot of weapons to?

224
00:19:18,560 --> 00:19:21,040
Was it that group of religious
fundamentalists...

225
00:19:21,120 --> 00:19:24,120
...who visited my state when
I was governor?

226
00:19:26,080 --> 00:19:29,680
Or was it the Saudis?

227
00:19:29,960 --> 00:19:35,160
Damn. It was them. I think
I better blame it on this guy. "

228
00:19:41,760 --> 00:19:44,240
In the days following
September 11 th...

229
00:19:44,440 --> 00:19:47,640
...all commercial and private airline
traffic was grounded.

230
00:19:47,720 --> 00:19:53,000
The FAA has taken the action to close
all of the airports in the United States.

231
00:19:53,080 --> 00:19:56,280
Even grounding the president's
father, former President Bush...

232
00:19:56,360 --> 00:19:58,480
...on a flight forced to land
in Milwaukee.

233
00:19:58,680 --> 00:20:02,080
Thousands of travelers were stranded,
among them Ricky Martin...

